<h2>HVAC Systems in Vermont</h2>
<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>Vermont's climate demands HVAC systems capable of handling temperature extremes ranging from -20¬∞F in winter to 85¬∞F+ in summer. The state's heating season typically spans from October through April, with peak demand occurring during January and February when temperatures can remain below freezing for weeks. Cooling requirements are generally modest, with only 10-15 days per year exceeding 85¬∞F, making energy-efficient heat pump systems ideal for year-round comfort while minimizing energy consumption.</p>

<p>For Vermont installations, HVAC professionals recommend systems with SEER ratings of 16-20 for cooling efficiency and HSPF ratings of 9.0 or higher for heating performance. Cold-climate heat pumps, specifically designed for northern regions, can provide efficient heating down to -15¬∞F or lower, making them increasingly popular alternatives to oil, propane, or electric resistance heating. These systems can achieve heating efficiencies of 200-300%, meaning they produce 2-3 times more heat energy than the electricity they consume.</p>

<p>Proper sizing and zoning are critical in Vermont due to the state's diverse housing stock, ranging from historic homes with minimal insulation to modern energy-efficient construction. Multi-zone mini-split systems allow homeowners to heat and cool only occupied areas, providing both comfort and energy savings. Additionally, backup heating systems are often recommended for extreme cold periods, though modern cold-climate heat pumps rarely require supplemental heating except during the coldest weather events.</p>

