<h2>Vermont Incentives & Rebates</h2>
<p>Vermont offers some of the most comprehensive incentive packages in New England for solar and HVAC installations, making it financially attractive for homeowners to upgrade their energy systems. The foundation of these savings starts with federal programs and is enhanced by generous state and utility incentives.</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Federal Solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC):</strong> The 30% federal tax credit remains the most significant incentive for solar installations through 2032. This credit applies to the full cost of solar equipment, installation, and related electrical work. For a \$20,000 solar system, homeowners can claim a \$6,000 credit directly against their federal tax liability. The credit can be carried forward if it exceeds the current year's tax liability, and there's no cap on the credit amount.</li>

<li><strong>Vermont Solar Rebate Program:</strong> The state offers rebates up to \$8,500 for residential solar installations, based on system size and customer type. Standard residential customers receive \$0.50 per watt up to 10kW, while low-income customers can receive up to \$1.25 per watt. This program is administered through the Clean Energy Development Fund and has specific requirements for installer certification and equipment standards.</li>

<li><strong>Green Mountain Power Incentives:</strong> Vermont's largest utility offers various programs including the "Bring Your Own Device" program for battery storage, heat pump rebates ranging from \$200-600 per unit, and time-of-use rates that can enhance solar savings. GMP also offers the innovative "Cow Power" program and has pioneered several customer-friendly renewable energy programs.</li>

<li><strong>Efficiency Vermont Heat Pump Rebates:</strong> As the state's energy efficiency utility, Efficiency Vermont provides rebates of \$200-1,200 for qualified heat pump installations, depending on the type and efficiency of the system. Additional rebates are available for heat pump water heaters (\$600-800) and comprehensive weatherization projects that can stack with heat pump incentives.</li>

<li><strong>Property Tax Exemption:</strong> Vermont law exempts the added value of renewable energy systems from property tax assessments, ensuring that solar installations won't increase property tax obligations while still adding value to the home for resale purposes.</li>
</ul>

